where:

Soggy Cattle
 Cattle from a backgrounding or growing operation that are fleshy or overly conditioned.

Stocker
Weaned cattle that are fed high roughage diets (including grazing) before going into feedlots.

Drunk Cattle
Cattle that are experiencing acidosis due to overconsumption or too rapid consumption of high-grain diets.

Eared Cattle
Cattle with significant Bos indicus (Brahman) breeding.

Fed cattle
Steers and heifers that have been fed concentrates, usually for 90 to 120 days in a feedlot.

Feeder cattle
Cattle that have been fed on forage but need further feeding on a high-energy rations before slaughter.

Finished cattle
Fed cattle whose time in the feed lot has been completed so that they are now ready for slaughter.

Grass Cattle
Cattle that were grown on pasture prior to placement in the feedlot.

Green Cattle
Cattle that are relatively thin, with only small amounts of body condition

Overeater
Cattle that eat too much on a high-grain diet.

Warmed-up Cattle
Cattle that have been grown in a backgrounding yard prior to being placed on feed.

Polled
Having no horns

Carry Cattle
Cattle that are held at the packing plant during a holiday or weekend. These cattle may be penned at the plant for 36 to 84 hours before being slaughtered. These cattle generally are offered feed and water if held for more than 36 hours.

Customer Cattle
Cattle that are owned by an investor, rancher or other client of the feedlot and fed and managed for a fee. Also see Company Cattle.

Properties.Description:
Characteristics that may be associated with an cattle livestock animal.

Ex:
- Soggy Cattle
- Stocker
- Drunk Cattle
- Eared Cattle
- Fed cattle
- Feeder cattle
- Finished cattle
- Grass Cattle
- Green Cattle
- Overeater
- Warmed-up Cattle
- Polled
- Carry Cattle
- Customer Cattle
- In Calf

where:

Soggy Cattle
 Cattle from a backgrounding or growing operation that are fleshy or overly conditioned.

Stocker
Weaned cattle that are fed high roughage diets (including grazing) before going into feedlots.

Drunk Cattle
Cattle that are experiencing acidosis due to overconsumption or too rapid consumption of high-grain diets.

Eared Cattle
Cattle with significant Bos indicus (Brahman) breeding.

Fed cattle
Steers and heifers that have been fed concentrates, usually for 90 to 120 days in a feedlot.

Feeder cattle
Cattle that have been fed on forage but need further feeding on a high-energy rations before slaughter.

Finished cattle
Fed cattle whose time in the feed lot has been completed so that they are now ready for slaughter.

Grass Cattle
Cattle that were grown on pasture prior to placement in the feedlot.

Green Cattle
Cattle that are relatively thin, with only small amounts of body condition

Overeater
Cattle that eat too much on a high-grain diet.

Warmed-up Cattle
Cattle that have been grown in a backgrounding yard prior to being placed on feed.

Polled
Having no horns

Carry Cattle
Cattle that are held at the packing plant during a holiday or weekend. These cattle may be penned at the plant for 36 to 84 hours before being slaughtered. These cattle generally are offered feed and water if held for more than 36 hours.

Customer Cattle
Cattle that are owned by an investor, rancher or other client of the feedlot and fed and managed for a fee. Also see Company Cattle.

In Calf
Pregnant cow
